<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06029p"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06029p">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06029p"> 29(p)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote>  &frac12;d ballad <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n06029p"><li>FW 42.13 </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/lexb.htm#n06029p">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/l39b.htm#n06029p">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n06029p">MS BL 47471b-2</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:027 <a name="b20d" href="../../FF/fdra/bda.htm#b20d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/b/b20d.htm#n06029p">Draft: I.2&sect;2.0</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">&lsquo;William Allingham&rsquo; In the preface to <i>The Music Master</i>, published in 1855, Allingham states that five of the songs or ballads, namely, <i>The Milkmaid</i>, <i>The Girl&apos;s Lamentation</i>, <i>Lovely Mary Donnelly</i>, <i>Nanny&apos;s Sailor Lad</i>, and <i>The Nobleman&apos;s Wedding</i>, have already had an Irish circulation as <mark>halfpenny ballads</mark>, and the first three were written for this purpose. <small> Alfred Perceval Graves, <a name="ILMS2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ILMS2"><cite title="source">Irish Literary and Musical Studies</cite></a>, (1913) 76</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
